    <li>
        <h5>
            Symbolic Ballistic Pendulum
        </h5>
        <p>
            A ballistic pendulum is a device for measuring the speed of a bullet.
            A diagram and brief explanation is available <a href = 'http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/balpen.html#c1'>here</a>.
            A bullet moving at a speed \( v_1\) of mass \( m \) strikes a stationary heavy pendulum of mass \( M \) in its equilibrium position.
            The collision is totally inelastic, that is, the bullet lodges into the pendulum.
            Immediately after the collision, the bullet-pendulum system is moving at a speed \( v_2 \).
            The bullet-pendulum system rises to some height \( y_f \), where it is briefly stationary before falling.
            Free-fall acceleration \( g \) is also a known variable in this problem.
        </p>
        <p>
            The ultimate goal is to gain a formula for the speed of the bullet \( v_1 \)
            in terms of the mass of the bullet \( m \), the mass of the pendulum \( M \),
            the height to which the pendulum-bullet system rises \( y_f \), and known constants.
            All three are all <emph>measurable variables</emph>,
            thus, with the formula we would have a system for measuring the speed of a bullet.
        </p>
        <p>
            The following steps will help you get an answer.
        </p>
        <ul type = 'a'>
            <li>
                Write an equation based on the conservation of momentum
                that relates the variables \( v_1 \), \( m \), \( M \), and \( v_2 \).
            </li>
            <li>
                Write an equation for the total energy of the pendulum-bullet-earth system
                immediately after the collision.
                Assume the zero-point height is the initial height of the pendulum,
                so at this point the system has only kinetic energy.
            </li>
            <li>
                Write an equation for the total energy of the pendulum-bullet-earth system
                after the pendulum has risen to a height \( y_f \).
            </li>
            <li>
                Create an equation based on the conservation of energy
                that relates the variables \( v_2 \), \( m \), \( M \), \( g \), and \( y_f \).
            </li>
            <li>
                Combine the equations based on the conservation of momentum with the equation based on the
                conservation of energy to determine a single formula for \( v_1 \) in terms of
                \( m \), \( M \), \( y_f \), and \( g \).
            </li>
            <li>
                Prove that your final answer is dimensionally correct.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ol>


<div class = 'pageBreak'></div>
<h3>
    Answers
</h3>

<p>
    Answer for ballistic pendulum:
    \( v_i = \frac{m + M}{m} \cdot \sqrt{2 g y_f} \)
</p>
